From: Igor Velkov <325961+iav@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Mon, 22 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: gpio: mvebu: allow two PWM lines on a single GPIO bank

Armada-38x style SoCs expose two PWM "blink" counters (A and B) shared by
all GPIO banks. The driver mapped one counter per GPIO chip (id 0 -> A,
id 1 -> B) and tracked a single requested line per chip, so a second PWM
line on the same bank was rejected with -EBUSY.

This is exactly the Helios4 case: both fans, j10-pwm (<&gpio1 9>) and
j17-pwm (<&gpio1 23>), hang off gpio1, so only the first one probes and
the second fails:

  pwm-fan j17-pwm: error -EBUSY: Could not get PWM
  pwm-fan j17-pwm: probe with driver pwm-fan failed with error -16

Publish each legacy bank's blink counter into a small SoC-global pool and
claim a counter per line. A PWM request now takes whichever counter is
free and routes the line to it via its bit in the bank's
GPIO_BLINK_CNT_SELECT register (0 -> A, 1 -> B). A single bank can
therefore drive both counters, giving the two Helios4 fans independent
duty/period. The hardware model is confirmed by the long-carried Kobol
"patch requirement" (which used the same SoC-global counter list on real
hardware) and by the upstream comment that "there are only two sets of
PWM configuration registers for all the GPIO lines".

Armada-8K keeps both counters within one bank's register block and
replicates that block per CP110, so a single SoC-global pair cannot
describe it. A8K banks therefore keep their counter to themselves (no
cross-bank borrowing, original one-PWM-per-bank behaviour preserved),
which also avoids the global pool aliasing two CP110 instances.

While reworking the request path:
- gpiochip_request_own_desc() may sleep, so it is moved out of the
  counter spinlock; a per-line bitmap (test_and_set_bit) rejects a
  duplicate request before the sleeping descriptor request.
- get_state() now reports the per-line blink-enable bit
  (GPIO_BLINK_EN & BIT(hwpwm)) instead of "any line on the bank enabled".

This is a fresh reimplementation of the Kobol fan patch, rebased onto the
post-LTS gpio-mvebu.c rework (devm_pwmchip_alloc / pwmchip_get_drvdata).

